message-stream (SSE); the streamed assistant message\n         404  chat not found / not owned by caller\n         400  malformed id / invalid body (ValidationPipe)\n         402  no model credential for the user (MissingModelCredentialError) — fail BEFORE any write\n         401  no/invalid session\n         409  message.id already has a completed turn (idempotent replay — see Concurrency & idempotency)\n```\n\n- The client sends **only the new message** — history is loaded server-side from the DB (verified against ai-chatbot: it does the same; the client is never trusted with history). This keeps the server authoritative and RLS-scoped.\n- The client supplies **`message.id`** (a UUID it generates — the AI SDK already does this). It is the **idempotency key**: the user message is stored under it, so a retry/reconnect with the same id is detectable rather than appended as a new prompt. (ai-chatbot also uses the client-supplied message id as the row id; RLS scopes inserts to the caller's own chat, so a client-chosen UUID is safe.)\n- A `POST` that returns a stream is the idiomatic AI SDK pattern; the resource created is the assistant message, delivered incrementally. The user message is created as a side effect of the same call (it has no independent lifecycle in v0.1).\n- DTO: `CreateMessageDto` (class-validator) — `message.id` is a UUID, `message.parts` non-empty, each text part non-blank, `@MaxLength` on text. Per the §22.0 DTO discipline.\n\n---\n\n## Core loop\n\nThe load-bearing rule: **no DB transaction is held open while the model streams.** DB work is two short `runAs` transactions — before and after the stream — with the model call in between holding nothing.\n\n```\n1. Guard → userId (verified). ParseUUIDPipe → chatId. ValidationPipe → { message.id, parts }.\n\n2. Fail-fast preconditions — NO writes happen until all of these pass:\n   a. credential = resolveModelCredential(userId)         # #54; missing → 402, history untouched\n      client = ModelsService.createOpenAIClient(credential, model)\n   b. runAs(userId) [read]: findById(chatId, userId) → 404 if absent / not owned\n   c. idempotency on message.id within this chat:\n        - exists WITH an assistant reply  → 409 / replay the stored answer; NO new model call\n        - exists WITHOUT a reply (prior attempt failed/aborted) → reuse that row; don't duplicate\n        - absent → continue\n\n3. runAs(userId) [short write tx #1, RLS engaged]:\n   a. persist the user message under the client-supplied message.id\n      (idempotent — a PK/unique conflict routes to step 2c); capture its seq → userSeq\n   b. history = chat messages WHERE seq <= userSeq, ordered by seq      # boundary cap (see below)\n   → buildContext(history, { systemPrompt })                            # pure, cache-aware (#53)\n\n4. result = client.streamText({\n     messages: context,\n     abortSignal: req.signal,                       # client disconnect → abort the model call\n     onFinish: async ({ text, usage, finishReason }) => {\n       runAs(userId) [short write tx #2]:            # persist assistant + usage; NO tx held during stream\n         MessagesRepository.create({ chatId, role:\"assistant\", senderUserId:null,\n                                     parts:[{type:\"text\", text}], usage, inReplyTo: message.id })\n     },\n   })\n5. return result.toUIMessageStreamResponse({ onError })   # SSE; onError → safe string, never a stack trace\n```\n\n- **Fail-fast ordering:** credential resolution, ownership, and the idempotency check all run **before** the user message is written — a 402/404/409 never mutates chat history (the original ordering wrote the user row first, so a missing-credential request polluted history and a retry duplicated it).\n- **Context boundary:** history is capped at `seq <= userSeq` (the just-created user message's sequence), so a concurrent send to the same chat cannot inject its message into this turn's context — each stream answers exactly its own prompt + prior history. `MessagesRepository.findByChatId` gains a `maxSeq` bound for this.\n- **Turn linkage:** the assistant row records `inReplyTo = message.id`, tying the answer to the prompting turn (also feeds #57 lineage).\n\nStopping: a single call with **no `stopWhen`/`maxSteps`** (those only matter with tools). The turn ends when the model finishes or the client aborts.\n\n---\n\n## Concurrency, idempotency & turn integrity\n\nA streamed turn has **durable side effects** (a persisted user message, a billed model call). The spec must define behavior under retries, reconnects, and concurrent sends — otherwise history corrupts and users get double-charged.\n\n- **Idempotency key = client `message.id`.** The user message is stored under it; a repeat POST with the same id (timeout retry, reconnect, double-click) is detected at step 2c, not appended:\n  - turn already **completed** (assistant reply exists) → `409` or replay the stored answer; **no new model call** (no double charge).\n  - prior attempt **failed/aborted** (user row exists, no assistant) → reuse the existing user row and re-attempt; never insert a second user row.\n  - The DB guarantee is the user message PK (the client UUID) + RLS chat-scoping; a duplicate insert conflicts and routes to the above.\n- **Context boundary** (`seq <= userSeq`): each turn builds context only up to its own user message, so overlapping sends to one chat cannot answer the wrong prompt.\n- **Generation serialization (recommended, not a hard v0.1 gate).** Even with the boundary cap, two concurrent sends to one chat run two generations (the second sees two user turns with no assistant between — degraded, not *wrong*). Fully serializing *one in-flight generation per chat* is the clean answer but **cannot be a held DB transaction** (that violates \"no tx during streaming\"). Later options: a per-chat advisory lock taken only for the short write txns + a `chat.generating` flag, or the durable-run queue (#48/#50, v0.2) which serializes by construction. v0.1 ships the boundary cap + idempotency (which prevent *corruption* and *double-charge*); strict single-flight ordering is deferred with this note rather than bolted on as a stream-spanning lock.\n- **Partial/failed turns:** the assistant row is written **only** in `onFinish` (clean finish). On in-stream error or abort, no assistant row is written; the user row remains, so a same-`message.id` retry resumes via the \"failed/aborted\" branch.\n\n## Harness boundary\n\n- **Model proposes** the answer text only (no actions — no tools in v0.1).\n- **Harness (apps/api) does** everything else: auth, ownership, persistence, context assembly, credential resolution, streaming transport, usage capture, error shaping. The model never touches the DB or the credential.\n\n## Instruction architecture\n\n- **System prompt** = a small static string, the **stable cacheable prefix** — `ContextBuilder` places it first and it contains **no per-request data** (no ids, timestamps, user values), so it is byte-identical across turns (prompt-cache floor). v0.1: a single hardcoded assistant system prompt (e.g. identity + answer-only behavior). Per-project/per-chat system prompts are a later milestone (§6–§7).\n- **History** = `ContextBuilder` output, oldest→newest, capped at `maxMessages` (hard cap; lineage compaction is #57). Sender-attribution prefix (already data-not-instruction) when >1 human sender.\n- No developer/user instruction layering beyond this in v0.1.\n\n## Tools\n\n**None.** Explicitly: no tool registry, no `tools`/`experimental_activeTools`, no `stopWhen`. (agents-best-practices: don't expose tools before a single-loop harness passes evals. ai-chatbot's 5 tools + approval flow are all \"extra\" we omit.)\n\n## Context & memory\n\n`ContextBuilder` (#53): `[system] → [history oldest→newest, capped]`, ordered by `seq` (deterministic — better than ai-chatbot's `createdAt` ordering, which ties for same-tx writes). No retrieval/RAG (v0.6). Compaction beyond the hard cap is #57.\n\n## Model layer & a required #54 extension\n\n`ModelClient` (#54) currently exposes `streamText({ messages, system, abortSignal })` and returns the AI SDK `StreamTextResult`. **#55 requires extending `ModelStreamInput` with `onFinish?: (e: { text: string; usage: LanguageModelUsage; finishReason: string }) => void | Promise<void>`** so the harness can capture the final text + token usage for persistence. (`createUIMessageStream`'s own `onFinish` yields `{ messages }` but **not** `usage` — usage lives on `streamText`'s `onFinish`/result. ai-chatbot never captures it; we do.) `onError` is handled at the loop via `toUIMessageStreamResponse({ onError })`, so it stays out of the client interface.\n\n**Credential source (v0.1 stopgap):** the user's key via `resolveModelCredential(userId, resolver)` (#54). v0.1 resolver may read a single configured key or a simple per-user store; the encrypted BYOK vault + per-scope resolution is v0.4. Missing credential → **402, before streaming**.\n\n## Safety\n\n- **Prompt-injection:** answer-only + **no tools** ⇒ minimal blast radius — injected instructions in chat content can at worst shape the text reply, not trigger an action. User/sender content is **data, not instruction** (ContextBuilder already treats it so). An injection probe is part of #58's eval set.\n- **Tenant isolation:** every DB touch is inside `runAs(userId)` → RLS; identity is the verified session id, never client input (#60). Cross-tenant write/read is impossible by construction.\n- **Secrets:** the model credential is resolved server-side, never logged, never sent to the client. The raw key never enters a response or the stream.\n- **Abort:** the request `AbortSignal` is wired into `streamText` so a client disconnect cancels the upstream model call (no orphaned generation / wasted spend).\n\n## Observability & cost (the #56 seam)\n\n- `onFinish` captures `usage` (`inputTokens`, `outputTokens`, and cached-input tokens where the provider reports them) and `fi